<TEXT>
twenty tons of rocket fuel 
burst into flame monday in a munitions igloo sending a cloud of 
smoke and fumes 1000 feet into the air officials said there were 
no injuries 
the blaze burned part of the domed storage area and scorched a 
2000squarefoot area of adjacent grass before being put out 1 
hours after it started said air force sgt louis aranabarradas 
lt col bruce rianda said there was no explosion but said the 
minuteman i missile propellant burned rapidly at this base about 20 
miles north of salt lake city 
there was no damage estimate but aranabarradas said the igloo 
was built to withstand this kind of stuff 
the cloud of smoke and fumes which rose 1000 feet above the 
igloo drifted south over the base and dispersed into the 
atmosphere base officials said in a statement 
taking into account the possibility that someone might have come 
into contact with remants of the cloud base environmental 
officials cautioned that the type of fire involved normally 
produces large amounts of hydrogen chloride gas which could 
irritate the nose throat and lungs the statement said 
an investigation into the fire was not expected to begin until 
noon tuesday because of a mandatory waiting period to allow the 
igloo to cool off before air force munitions crews can enter 
aranabarradas said 
