<TEXT>
murphys law caught up with the murphy bed when 
a federal appeals court ruled that the name of the famous folddown 
bed is now so commonly used that its no longer protected by 
trademark laws 
we hold that murphy bed is a generic term having been 
appropriated by the public to designate generally a type of bed 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals said monday in overturning 
part of a lower court ruling 
the 2nd circuit ruled that a federal judge on long island erred 
in finding companies in georgia and florida both named murphy bed 
co of america inc had infringed on the trademark rights of the 
murphy door bed co which was founded in 1925 by the inventor of 
the disappearing bed 
but like murphys law in which anything that can go wrong will 
the appeals court also had some bad news for the murphy bed 
imitators 
we agree with the district court that defendants engaged in 
unfair competition by passing off beds of their own manufacture as 
beds of the murphy co which is based in amittyville 
the court also affirmed us district judge jacob mishlers 
injunction which bars the two companies from using the term 
murphy bed 
at the turn of the century william lawrence murphy invented a 
bed that could be concealed in a wall closet when not in use he 
patented the idea in 1918 
at least twice murphy successfully convinced imitators who 
marketed their products as murphy beds to use a different name 
but the appeals court noted that in 1981 and in 1982 the 
federal patent and trademark office refused the murphy cos bid to 
register murphy bed as a trademark and a trademark appeals 
board found in 1984 that murphy bed has for a long period of time 
been used by a substantial segment of the public as a generic term 
for a bed which folds into a wall or closet 
while affirming the 6330 in damages awarded the murphy door 
bed co for breach of contract the appeals court dismissed the 
801161 awarded in compensatory damages and sent the case back to 
mishler for a recalculation based on the florida and georgia 
companies net profits 
court papers did not specify in which cities the companies are 
based 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

