<TEXT>
in its final days this countrys 
election campaign is getting nasty even by central americas 
roughandtumble standards 
stumping opposition candidates for the presidency and other 
national and local posts call government leaders treacherous slime 
thugs and thieves 
the eightparty progovernment coalition counters with a 
television ad featuring president bush speaking with a bogus 
voiceover in english with spanish subtitles 
the voiceover picking up on a published report has bush 
admitting he authorized 10 million to subsidize opposition 
parties although the us administration has not commented on the 
report 
washington contends forces loyal to panamas de facto leader 
gen manuel antonio noriega intend to rig sundays election 
billboards proclaiming the charms of opposition presidential 
candidate guillermo endara have had large american flag decals 
pasted on them with the slogan for 10 million he sold out his 
country 
much of the vilification has been undertaken in the name of two 
dead men gen omar torrijos the charismatic dictator who died in 
a plane crash in 1981 and arnulfo arias madrid the grand old man 
of the panamanian opposition 
arias was thrown out of the presidency three times by coups and 
died last year at age 87 
both men had large almost fantaical cultlike personal 
followings something both endara and progovernment candidate 
carlos duque lack 
even some of endaras posters carry pictures not of him but of 
arias duques ads rarely mention his name without invoking the 
memory of torrijos the prime mover in getting the united states to 
agree to turn the panama canal over to panama at the end of the 
century 
this weeks cocktail party joke goes like this 
torrijos and arias meet in heaven you look a little tired 
observes torrijos 
you look a little worn yourself replies arias 
i know says the general maybe we should stop campaigning 
so hard 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
just over a year ago relations both personal and diplomatic 
were smooth between the united states and panama after noriega was 
indicted on drugrunning charges by two us grand juries they 
went sour almost overnight 
the united states tried to force out noriega through economic 
sanctions but failed and the relationship has since been as tense 
as any washington has 
american diplomats are prohibited from speaking to some of their 
panamanian counterparts the united states is blamed for every 
conceivable ill and volunteer dignity battalions are training 
to fend off the yankee invasion that has been predicted any day now 
for the past year 
headlines in a governmentrun newspaper announced that in the 
face of a threat of a yankee invasion the neighborhoods of the 
rich will be the battlefields and that gringo spies traitors 
and those who sell their country will be executed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the us armys southern command in charge of defending the 
panama canal has issued press passes to visiting reporters to help 
them gain entry to military bases 
a government advertisement in one newapaper monday said anybody 
caught carrying the pass would be arrested as an american spy 
the approximately 12000 american troops in panama will go on 
alert status saturday because of predicted disturbances in the 
capital the alert calls for troops to try to avoid leaving base if 
possible 
american troops were once something of an industry here but the 
freewheeling entertainment zones near their bases are quiet today 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
despite the negative tone of the campaign there is a refreshing 
lightness to some of it 
latin jazz bands packed into pickups drive around displaying 
