<TEXT>
a federal judges ruling that illinois 
death penalty law is unconstitutional could help to resolve legal 
questions that have loomed since it was enacted in 1977 experts 
say 
us district judge harold baker said monday the law gives 
prosecutors too much leeway in deciding when to seek the death 
penalty violating us supreme court rulings that states must 
ensure capital punishment is not imposed in an arbitrary and 
capricious manner 
if higher courts agree bakers decision would invalidate the 
sentences of the 121 men currently facing the death penalty in 
illinois among them is john w gacy convicted of killing 33 young 
men and boys in the worst multiplekilling case in us history 
bakers decision marked the first time a federal judge has ruled 
on the constitutionality of illinois death penalty law the us 
supreme court has never agreed to hear an illinois death penalty 
case 
in the past legal experts have said a final resolution of the 
issue was unlikely until federal courts addressed a case focusing 
solely on the constitutional question 
i think weve finally got a case where the issue has been 
squarely addressed in the district court and will be squarely 
addressed on appeal said david bradford a chicago attorney who 
has handled appeals of death row inmates 
illinois attorney general neil hartigan said the state would 
appeal the ruling to the 7th us circuit court of appeals in 
chicago michael ficaro hartigans first assistant said he was 
confident bakers ruling would be overturned 
the illinois supreme court has dealt with that issue over 60 
times he said we believe the statute is constitutional 
because of prolonged appeals no one has been executed under the 
1977 statute 
jay miller director of the illinois chapter of the american 
civil liberties union said we think theyre all 
unconstitutional i dont think theres any way to write a death 
penalty law thats constitutional 
bakers ruling came in the case of a man who demanded the death 
penalty after being convicted in 1980 of killing two people in 
vermilion county 
appeals on behalf of charles silagy reached the state supreme 
court twice and the us supreme court once but were unsuccessful 
until his case reached baker in one of the last stages of the 
appeals process 
the states capital punishment law allows a trial court to 
consider a death sentence in certain circumstances such as a 
multiple killing but only when requested by the prosecution 
in 1979 the state supreme court ruled 43 that the prosecutors 
authority to seek the death penalty is not significantly different 
than their power to seek criminal prosecution 
but baker sided with the dissenting justices in that case 
our statute contains no directions or guidelines to minimize 
the risk of wholly arbitrary and capricious action by the 
prosecutor in either requesting or in not requesting a death 
sentence hearing wrote justice howard c ryan whose opinion 
was cited by baker 
