a mysterious oil spill in march that 
contaminated beaches on two islands has been traced to an 
interisland cruise ship the coast guard announced 
oil samples taken from ss independence matched samples taken 
from beaches on lanai and molokai and from a slick between the 
islands capt gordon piche told reporters monday 
attorney robert frame who represents american hawaii cruises 
which operates the boat said the company was cooperating with the 
coast guard but would do its own investigation to check the 
findings 
the company will abide by whatever laws apply he said 
under federal water pollution control laws the company could 
face a maximum civil penalty of 5000 and would have to repay the 
government for the cost of the cleanup which is estimated at more 
than 100000 piche said 
the findings will be turned over to a coast guard hearings 
officer within six weeks piche said it will be up to the us 
attorneys office to press criminal charges which carry a maximum 
penalty of a 10000 fine he added 
piche said the boat apparently dumped about 10000 gallons of 
bunker fuel oil into the ocean by accident while pumping fresh 
water out of ballast tanks on the night of march 24 
the spill washed ashore along a 10mile stretch of the east end 
of molokai and along 10 miles of the northeast side of lanai there 
have been no reports of any damage to wildlife piche said 
company officials were informed monday of the findings and 
their reaction was they didnt see how it could have happened 
piche said 
