jury selection began today in the trial 
of a man accused of killing his two sons in a redhot foundry ladle 
on thanksgiving day 1987 
muskegon county circuit judge james graves jr rejected a motion 
by an attorney for defendant bartley james dobben for a nonjury 
trial 
dobben 28 who has been diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic 
has been shuffled among the states psychiatric centers since his 
arrest on nov 26 1987 
on that day dobben his wife susan and their children 
2yearold bartley and 15monthold peter were on their way to a 
family thanksgiving dinner when dobben pulled into the parking lot 
of the cannonmuskegon corp foundry where he worked in norton 
shores 
he left his pregnant wife in the car telling her he wanted to 
retrieve a bible and show his sons the operation 
minutes later dobben allegedly placed the boys in a huge 
foundry ladle used to hold molten metal and turned on the gas jets 
until the ladle reached 1300 degrees the boys quickly suffocated 
as the ladle became a searing cauldron autopsies showed 
dobbens attorney terry nolan contends his client should be 
found innocent by reason of insanity 
brett gardner an assistant muskegon county prosecutor says 
ample evidence exists to show dobben was criminally responsible for 
the slayings 
dobben has a long history of mental illness court records show 
that family members had him committed to the kalamazoo regional 
psychiatric hospital because they were frightened by his actions 
a september 1985 probate court order said dobben could be 
reasonably expected within the near future to intentionally or 
unintentionally seriously injure himself or others 
those suffering from paranoid schizophrenia live in a fantasy 
world and may have hallucinations or false perceptions and hear 
voices psychiatrists say 
after his release from the hospital dobben was given 
prescriptions for powerful drugs to control his behavior but 
family members said he often refused to take them especially after 
his religious views moved increasingly out of the mainstream 
he began to associate with a small fundamentalist group called 
emmanuel fellowship led by rood vaughan an unordained preacher 
and used car salesman 
vaughan who was to be called as a witness checked himself into 
the kalamazoo regional psychiatric hospital saturday one day after 
police said he attacked his mother she suffered a sprained wrist 
in the altercation 
it isnt known how vaughans hospitalization might affect 
dobbens trial which has been postponed several times as 
psychiatrists debated the defendants competency 
