<TEXT>
the aids crisis has generated nationwide support 
for sex education but taken attention away from other important 
sexual topics like pregnancy prevention according to a survey 
released tuesday 
support for sex education is strong not only does a large 
majority of the american public support it but so do most state 
education agencies and large school districts concluded the 
study risk and responsibility teaching sex education in 
americas schools today 
but the report found that of the nearly 63 million states 
spent in 198788 on sex education curricula 51 million was 
specifically for aids instruction 
forty states either support or require sex education said the 
study by the alan guttmacher institute 
but jeannie rosoff president of the institute said that states 
have abdicated their role in sex education by giving districts 
only vague guidelines on how to teach it and by not setting teacher 
certification standards 
the study also found that nearly one third of sex education 
teachers said their biggest problem was pressure from parents the 
community or administrators especially when dealing with 
homosexuality condoms or abortion 
the 323000 study funded primarily by the carnegie corp of 
new york examined teaching policies and methods in grades 712 
the findings were published in family planning perspectives a 
bimonthly publication of the guttmacher institute a private 
nonprofit research group that studies reproductive health 
the study consisted of three nationwide mailed surveys conducted 
in the spring of 1988 one polled 4241 of the estimated 50000 
public school teachers who teach sex education a second surveyed 
all 50 state education departments and the district of columbia 
regarding sex education laws policies and curricula the third 
asked similar questions of 162 large school districts 
it concluded that the crisis orientation created by aids has 
led educators to stress the negative outcomes of sex while 
often neglecting other important issues 
in only six states connecticut hawaii massachusetts 
michigan new jersey and vermont are condoms discussed 
explicitly michigans curriculum discusses where condoms can be 
bought and new jerseys suggests ways of teaching students how to 
use them 
five other states alabama new york north carolina ohio and 
oklahoma discuss condoms but in a negative light usually 
stressing the failure rate new yorks curriculum extols abstinence 
as freedom from the bother and dangers of the pill iud and other 
contraceptives 
the curricula leave something to be desired in terms of 
balance said asta m kenney a coauthor of the study 
eight out of 10 teachers surveyed said they could use help in 
teaching about pregnancy prevention and sexually transmitted 
diseases 
mary hatwood futrell president of the national education 
association said the study demonstrates the need for better 
teacher training 
our public schools must provide teachers with the necessary 
tools and resources to conduct effective sex education at all 
levels she said 
twentynine percent of teachers complained of inadequate 
materials and 25 percent said students were a problem because they 
were embarrassed or ignorant about sex 
among other findings 
46 states plus the district of columbia support aids education 
and 43 plus the district of columbia support instruction about 
other sexually transmitted diseases fortythree support the 
teaching of abstinence 
32 states require or encourage instruction on pregnancy 
prevention alabama discourages such instruction and utah prohibits 
it only delaware and georgia specify contraception methods and 
outline the risks and benefits of each 
half the states require some kind of training or certification 
to teach sex education but only michigan ohio utah and the 
district of columbia require teachers to have taken a course in 
human sexuality 
87 percent of large districts have sex or aids curricula and 96 
percent cover the negative aspects of teenage sex more than 70 
percent of the districts discuss abstinence as the best alternative 
in grades 710 but such lessons drop off to 50 percent in grades 
11 and 12 
