<TEXT>
a team of navy specialists has concluded that 
the gun turret aboard the battleship iowa damaged in last months 
deadly explosion can be repaired but no decision has been made to 
do so the pentagon said tuesday 
dan howard the defense departments chief spokesman said a 
35member navy damage control team began its work aboard the 
battleship last week by determining that the materials and 
expertise are available to repair the turret 
the answer to that basic question had not been clear in the 
immediate aftermath of the april 19 tragedy because of the vessels 
age the iowa was commissioned in 1943 during world war ii and no 
vessel of its type has been built since that war 
fortyseven sailors died in the explosion inside the no 2 gun 
turret while they were loading a 16inch gun with powder 
the fact that repairs are technically feasible however does 
not mean the navy has decided to make repairs howard said no cost 
estimate has been developed yet nor is any estimate available on 
how long such repairs might take he said 
the iowas skipper capt fred p moosally has said the vessel 
would be ready for battle even if the damaged turret was never 
repaired the huge battleship still has two other turrets each 
with three 16inch guns 
preliminary examination indicates that it can be repaired 
howard said tuesday but there are a lot of factors that go into 
a final decision 
its too early yet to give you either a cost estimate or the 
amount of time it would take to make repairs all i can give you is 
the preliminary judgment that they can repair it 
the spokesman said one of the first indications repairs might be 
feasible came recently when the huge guns above the damaged turret 
were swung back on centerline using their own internal machinery 
in related developments howard said the battleship had been 
moved to a new anchorage near norfolk va to unload the gunpowder 
and shells from the damaged turret 
you may recall that as part of the safety procedures they 
flooded the magazine on the ship immediately following the 
explosion now they have to take out the powder and projectiles to 
examine them and see if they were damaged by the water 
the spokesman also said he had investigated but could not 
confirm a published report that one of the iowas victims issued a 
terse verbal warning that there was a problem just before the 
blast 
the washington post said tuesday a crew member reportedly made 
the comment over a soundactivated phone circuit just before the 
explosion saying uh oh weve got a problem here 
i cant get any corroboration for that story howard said 
i just dont know 
