<TEXT>
senate democrats launched a campaign tuesday 
to wean american farmers from dependence on pesticides and 
fertilizers arguing that new practices are needed to protect food 
and water from chemical contamination 
the centerpiece of their effort is legislation sponsored by sen 
wyche fowler dga and endorsed at a news conference by senate 
majority leader george mitchell of maine sen patrick leahy 
dvt chairman of the senate agriculture committee and 23 farm 
and environmental groups 
fowler chairman of the agriculture subcommittee on conservation 
and forestry said the goal is to provide through the 1990 farm 
bill programs to give incentives to farmers who voluntarily reduce 
reliance on chemicals 
there have been methods time proven for 3000 years where a 
proper combination of conservation practices stewardship 
practices crop rotation practices along with an appropriate use 
of chemicals and fertilizers have proven effective he said 
the legislation would require that the department of agriculture 
inform farmers about advances in lowinput farming integrated pest 
management and any other practice reducing reliance on chemicals 
without sacrificing production 
it also would remove existing disincentives in federal farm 
programs that prevent farmers from taking advantage of new 
lowinput farming methods and it would provide incentives to 
encourage farmers to make the transition from an overreliance on 
chemicals to lowinput methods 
for too long industry and agriculture policies have promoted 
practices that degrade our natural and agricultural resources and 
pose threats to the health of our people fowler said we have 
already waited longer than we should to reverse this trend and 
restore american agriculture to a safe sound course for the 
future 
both fowler and mitchell said they expect farmers eventually 
will support the legislation even though the transition might 
initially reduce crop yields and profits 
farm families will benefit from this bill mitchell said 
by helping to reduce pesticide use this legislation will help 
protect the quality of drinking water in rural areas 
the bill would create a drinking water welltesting program to 
detect contamination by pesticides or nitrates in areas where 
testing finds contamination federal aid would be provided to help 
farmers establish groundwater protection plans 
mitchell said encouraging farmers to reduce use of pesticides 
and fertilizers also will help protect the nations food supply 
while the vast majority of our food products are free of 
pesticide contamination we must do everything we can to expand and 
improve our food quality programs he said this bill will take 
us in that direction 
</TEXT>
