<TEXT>
the bush administration is reviewing its 
policy on boarding foreign vessels on the high seas after us 
personnel were barred for three days from searching a taiwanese 
ship suspected of illegal salmon fishing a state department 
official said tuesday 
ed wolfe the state departments ambassador for oceans and 
fisheries told a house subcommittee that an interagency task 
force was examining the policy which allows for the boarding of a 
foreign vessel only after receiving permission from the government 
whose flag the ship flies 
because of the recent incident invovling taiwan we are 
reviewing our highseas boarding policy wolfe said i am 
confident we will come up with something 
wolfe said the united states has jurisdiction over such fish as 
salmon that were born in us waters and return there to spawn 
after several years in the ocean 
the problem is what we do with that jurisdiction wolfe said 
during a hearing before the fisheries wildlife conservation and 
environment subcommittee of the house merchant marine and fisheries 
committee 
wolfe said the present policy is based on customary 
international law and in a brief interview after the hearing 
declined to discuss possible alternatives 
we are exploring various possibilities wolfe said 
northwest lawmakers said that fishermen in alaska washington 
and oregon are becomming increasingly angry over what the illegal 
catch of us salmon by foreign driftnet fleets from tawian south 
korean and japan 
alaska republican rep don young said the only way to get the 
attention of the three countries with driftnet fleets would be to 
impose trade sanctions 
coast guard rear adm ted leland told the subcommittee that us 
personnel who boarded the taiwanese vessel in the north pacific 
last month found no conclusive evidence it had been illegally 
fishing for salmon 
the cutter jarvis shadowed the taiwanese ship for more than 700 
miles before coast guard personnel were given permission from the 
government of tawian to board efforts to find the ships net 
which was abandoned after the vessel was first spotted by the 
jarvis were unsucessful 
under various diplomatic agreements driftnet fishing has been 
limited to areas well away from the migration routes of salmon 
since congress enacted a law in late 1987 the state department 
has been trying to negotiate driftnet monitoring and enforcement 
agreements with each of the three countries 
if such agreements are not concluded by june 29 the president 
can then impose trade restrictions on imports of fish products from 
those countries 
american fishermen claim that vessels from taiwan south korea 
and japan are using driftnets to illegally snare millions of tons 
of salmon under the guise of squid fishing fishing groups have 
said the illegal fishing has already affected salmon runs in 
alaska washington and oregon 
an estimated 700 fishing boats from taiwan south korea and 
japan use driftnets which can stretch 35 miles in length and cover 
more than 30000 square miles of ocean on any given day 
environmentalists have likened driftnet fishing to clear cutting 
a forest and charge the nets are responsible for the deaths of 
thousands of porpoises seals seabirds and other marine life 
annually 
</TEXT>
