<TEXT>
the us international trade commission ruled 
tuesday that the domestic bearing industry has been harmed by 
lowpriced imports clearing the way for the final imposition of 
antidumping duties on certain imports from europe and asia 
in one of the nations largest antidumping cases ever the 
commerce department will decide the amount of duties that the 
customs service will levy on an estimated 531 million in imported 
bearings from nine nations 
in a series of six rulings the commission found injury to us 
bearing producers from lowpriced imports of ball cylindrical 
roller and plain bearings and rejected claims of injury from 
imports of spherical needle roller and slewing ring bearings 
the action was hailed by the torrington co of torrington 
conn which had filed a petition on behalf of the us bearing 
industry in march 1988 claiming that massive dumping by foreign 
countries was damaging domestic manufacturers of antifriction 
bearings 
torrington president thomas e bennett said the commissions 
action should help create conditions of fair competition in the 
us market he said domestic producers lost an estimated 700 
million in sales a year because of unfairly priced imports 
bennett said the company was disappointed that not all 
categories of imported bearings were found to be injuring domestic 
manufacturers and that torrington will not hesitate to take 
strong action again to challenge additional unfair trade practices 
that are identified 
terence stewart a washington attorney representing the company 
said torringtons petition covered 625 million in imports a year 
and that the commissions action would result in the imposition of 
duties on 85 percent of those imports torrington a subsidiary of 
ingersollrand co is the nations largest producer of a range of 
bearings 
stewart said the ruling was significant because for literally 
thousands of americans it will provide employment opportunities in 
a highskilled industry he said an estimated 30 us plants had 
closed and 14000 jobs had been lost because of unfair competition 
from abroad 
stewart said that while the itc ruling was the last step before 
final imposition of duties the decision still could be challenged 
in court and that litigation was not unlikely given the hardfought 
nature of the case to date 
itc spokesman jim craig said the customs service would probably 
begin collecting duties by the middle of the month the decision 
covers certain imports from germany france italy japan romania 
singapore sweden thailand and the united kingdom 
stewart said most of the affected imports were ball bearings 
and that the largest share of the imports came from germany and 
japan 
in earlier rulings on the case the commerce department had 
found final dumping margins ranging up to 212 percent for some 
imported bearings meaning that us prices for the imports would 
have to be raised by that amount to bring them to a fair value 
the itc estimated there were 95 domestic producers of 
antifriction bearings in 1988 with plants located in alabama 
arkansas california connecticut georgia illinois indiana 
iowa kentucky michigan new hampshire new jersey new york 
north carolina ohio oklahoma pennsylvania south carolina 
tennessee virginia and wisconsin 
antifriction bearings are used in the aircraft automotive 
machinery and electronics industries 
commission chairman anne brunsdale recused herself from all 
votes on the bearings to avoid any potential conflict of interest 
given certain family holdings in affected industries 
