<TEXT>
the outgoing chairman of the federal 
communications commission pointed with pride tuesday to an opening 
up of competition in broadcasting during the seismic change of 
his six years at the agency 
in a swan song address to industry executives dennis patrick 
ticked off a list of benefits he said broadcasters had received 
since he joined the fcc in 1983 
he thanked his audience at the national association of 
broadcasters convention for being courageous soldiers in this 
battle for freedom and for unflagging support of his policies 
against critics in congress and nonbroadcast media 
through this period of seismic change i have held firmly 
to the notion of open entry to create a competitive marketplace for 
the media he said this policy has led to a proliferation of 
information outlets unimaginable even six years ago 
the average american home today has access to 25 video channels 
he said and half of all americans receive at least 28 radio 
stations 
we have tried to foster competition at the fcc by lowering 
barriers to entry and by permitting broadcasters to compete as 
freely as those with whom they compete namely cable patrick 
said 
