during patricks tenure the fcc repealed the fairness doctrine 
that required broadcasters to air opposing views in controversial 
issues congress is expected to vote to reinstate the policy this 
year posing a possible veto fight with president bush 
the fcc also revised the means by which stations renew their 
licenses to bar sham competitors who just want money to drop their 
challenges to licensees 
no longer will you be held hostage to petitions to deny filed 
because you refuse to concede to extortion nor will we tolerate 
those who seek to extort cash payments by masquerading as competing 
applicants patrick said to a round of applause 
he also noted the fccs decision last year to make sure that a 
us standard for highdefinition television will not make obsolete 
the huge investment tv stations have in current equipment 
american industry is racing to adopt standards with which to 
build an hdtv system and stave off the expected appearance in the 
next couple of years of foreignmade hdtv vcrs and movies 
he urged the broadcasters not to delay reaching agreement on an 
hdtv transmission standard so america can regain the lead in 
broadcast technology 
he also said broadcasters need further protection from the cable 
tv industry in the form of a requirement that cable systems pay for 
the overtheair programs they feed to their subscribers 
they should no longer be permitted to take the product that 
you have bought you have promoted you have earned and pass it 
off without asking as theirs patrick said to more applause 
he said the future holds new challenges for broadcasters 
fiberoptic cable and telephone entry into video programming 
competition from foreign media further loss of audience and the 
shifting of advertising from video to point of sales 
he said network affiliates and networks may have to forge 
stronger bonds and broadcasters may have to work with cable to 
survive against global competitors 
in this complex future he said may you have convictions 
may you have the courage of your convictions may you succeed 
patricks address concluded the 67th annual nab gathering which 
was attended by a record 50136 broadcast executives and exhibitors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

