<TEXT>
a food and drug administration advisory 
committee on tuesday recommended approval of a drug used to treat 
an aidsrelated condition that can lead to blindness 
the panel of outside experts based its decision on new data that 
came from several recent studies conducted in the united states and 
in other countries that found the drug ganciclovir is effective in 
treating cytomegalovirus retinitis in aids patients 
this is the second aids drug the advisory committee has 
recommended for approval in two days of hearings on monday the 
panel recommended approval of the aerosolized version of 
pentamidine to ward off initial and recurring bouts of pneumocystis 
carinii pneumonia which kills 60 percent of aids patients 
fda approval of ganciclovir is expected this summer and 
approval of aerosol pentamidine is likely within weeks said an fda 
source who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
advocates of programs to fight aids have been pushing the fda to 
move quickly on approving the drugs 
ganciclovir has been widely available to aids patients since 
november when the fda approved use of the drug for treatment of 
patients who were in the immediate sightthreatening stage of 
cytomegalovirus retinitis 
in early march the fda made the drug available to patients 
whose cytomegalovirus infection was in an early stage 
the advisory committee recommended against approval of the drug 
in october 1987 citing the need for more safety and efficacy data 
in recommending approval this time the panel also strongly 
urged that extensive followup studies be conducted after the drug 
is on the market the committee specifically recommended a study to 
determine the drugs proposed use in children and a study comparing 
ganciclovir with foscarnet another experimental drug for 
cytomegalovirus retinitis 
the panel also urged a study be conducted to determine whether 
ganciclovir can be used in patients who are receiving zidovudine 
or azt which has been shown to prolong survival of aids patients 
because the two drugs have similar toxicity they arent used 
together 
</TEXT>
