<TEXT>
cardinal giuseppe siri the archbishop of 
genoa and a perennial candidate for the papacy died at home 
tuesday evening of a heart ailment an official at the diocesan 
chancellery said he was 82 
siri a cardinal since 1953 attended four conclaves the 
meetings in which popes are elected he was described as pope pius 
xiis choice to succeed him and in the last two conclaves was a 
leading votegetter in early balloting 
he was frequently depicted as an archconservative who opposed 
many of the reforms of pope john xxiii and who tried to block 
progressive initiatives during the vatican ii council held from 
196265 
but siri rejected the conservative label in a rare interview 
with the genoa newspaper il lavoro 
if i had to describe myself i would describe myself as an 
independent a man who walks alone and is not a member of any 
group he said 
a staunch anticommunist he nonetheless maintained working 
relations with the socialistcommunist alliance running genoa 
siri believed that laymen must obey the clergy and that the 
clergy had to make all possible efforts to be available anywhere 
at any time to laymen in genoa he made sure chaplains were on 
duty in major factories and he encouraged priests to celebrate 
mass in parishioners homes 
siri was born in genoa on may 20 1906 the son of a stevedore 
he attended the pontifical gregorian university where he earned a 
doctorate in theology 
ordained a priest at 22 his early career was mainly in the 
framework of catholic action a church organization that seeks to 
involve laymen in church activities 
he wrote several books the best known being theology for 
laymen 
siri was particularly remembered for his resourcefulness during 
world war ii when as auxiliary bishop of genoa he negotiated 
with nazi forces surrounding the city and met secretly with 
partisan leaders eventually arranging a nazi surrender that 
avoided further bombardment of the city 
he became archbishop of genoa in 1946 at the time of his 
resignation in july 1987 he was the last remaining active cardinal 
named by pope pius xii 
</TEXT>
