<TEXT>
economic ideologies with their code words and 
slogans may persist in the abstract long after they have been 
questioned and sometimes even abandoned in practice 
it happens in every system but nowhere more dramatically at the 
moment than in eastern europe where the centrally planned 
economies of the soviet union poland and hungary have been 
flirting with private enterprise 
in the soviet union a fifth of the nations 50000 farms have 
begun leasing land and equipment to individuals and families 
poland has authorized 23000 private coops in hungary the 
budapest stock market has been reopened 
less abrupt changes are under way in bulgaria and in the soviet 
republics of estonia lithuania and latvia where national identity 
has remained vitally alive there has been pressure for the 
legalization of private property 
privatization is a worldwide trend says the reason foundation 
which exists to promote private enterprise in 1988 it says 
governments shifted 43 billion of functions and responsibilities 
to the private sector 
when that happens in the united states which sold conrail for 
16 billion in 1987 or in britain where the british airport 
authority was privatized it isnt startling news because such 
things have been proposed for years 
eastern europe where governments scorned private enterprise 
since world war ii is another matter seeking to raise production 
through individual initiative some startling changes have 
occurred these are excerpts from reasons 1988 report 
soviet union 
in a reversal after 50 years of collectivized agriculture the 
soviet union began allowing individual farmers and groups of 
farmers to rent land from the state in a move that essentially 
marks a return to family farming 
legislation was enacted allowing farmers to buy tractors trucks 
and other socalled means of production that formerly could be 
acquired only through state enterprises farmers were permitted to 
hire workers as long as they met wage levels in state enterprises 
the government also authorized the sale of stateowned homes to 
tenants apartments can be sold on receipt of 50 percent of the 
units value with the remainder to be paid over 10 years 
poland 
commencing in 1988 some 23000 private cooperatives were given 
permission to operate though only half had become operative by the 
end of the year they include restaurants butcher shops shoe 
repair shops and plumbing services 
in another broadening of reforms polish enterprises can employ 
up to 50 workers per shift formerly private enterprises had been 
limited to only 10 workers per shift 
poland also is removing import duties on some western goods and 
will allow foreign investors to own 100 percent of some polish 
enterprises theres a downside a graduated income tax takes 90 
percent on upper incomes 
hungary 
in addition to the opening of the budapest stock market in 1988 
private stock ownership is now possible previously only state 
banks and cooperatives could purchase shares in the 40 stateowned 
companies that have issued stock 
private individuals also may form limited companies these 
companies can employ as many as 500 workers just last year more 
than 100 joint ventures were set up with foreigners 
such changes in eastern europe might be phases or experiments 
but the motivation for them contains an ideological message 
underlying all of them is the belief that if unleashed individual 
initiative produces wondrous things 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
