the only gasoline station in the small 
town of echo ore has closed and the same fate may be in store 
for a string of others a result of tougher federal regulations on 
underground storage tanks 
dennis gronquist arlington mayor and texaco franchise owner 
said there soon may be no stations in the 160 miles between the 
eastern oregon communities of arlington and john day 
he said station owners and consumers are just beginning to feel 
the effects of us environmental protection agency regulations 
intended to prevent gasoline leaks from underground storage tanks 
the epa estimates 43 percent of all service stations in the 
nation with underground tanks will close within the first five 
years the policies are in effect 
gasoline station owners are being required to upgrade tanks 
install leakage detection devices and obtain leakage accident 
insurance estimates of the cost range from 12000 to 50000 per 
station not including insurance 
were going to lose all our service stations because nobody 
can afford it said herb wright owner of wrights chevrolet in 
fossil 
but ronald moyer a state department of environmental quality 
tank specialist noted that leakage from underground tanks has 
sometimes resulted in buildings being blown up or in contamination 
of a citys water supply 
entire communities could be left without water if somebodys 
tank leaked moyer said 
